  "prompt": "What is the chemical reaction when acetic acid is combined with sodium hydroxide (NaOH)?",
  "response": "When acetic acid (CH\u2083COOH) is combined with sodium hydroxide (NaOH), a neutralization reaction occurs. The reaction produces sodium acetate (CH\u2083COONa) and water (H\u2082O). The balanced chemical equation for this reaction is:\n\n\\[\n\\text{CH\u2083COOH} + \\text{NaOH} \\rightarrow \\text{CH\u2083COONa} + \\text{H\u2082O}\n\\]\n\nIn more detail, the acetic acid (a weak acid) donates a proton (H\u207a) to the hydroxide ion (OH\u207b) from the sodium hydroxide (a strong base), forming water. The remaining acetate ion (CH\u2083COO\u207b) combines with the sodium ion (Na\u207a) to form sodium acetate, which is a salt.\n\nThe ionic form of the reaction can be written as:\n\\[\n\\text{CH\u2083COOH} + \\text{OH\u207b} \\rightarrow \\text{CH\u2083COO\u207b} + \\text{H\u2082O}\n\\]\n\nThis reaction is exothermic, meaning it releases heat. It is a typical example of an acid-base neutralization reaction.",
